DOCUMENT();        # This should be the first executable line in the problem.

loadMacros("PG.pl",
           "PGbasicmacros.pl",
           "PGchoicemacros.pl",
           "PGanswermacros.pl",
           "PGauxiliaryFunctions.pl",
                "extraAnswerEvaluators.pl");


$a = random(2,4,1);
$b = random(2,4,1);
$c = random(1,4,1);


TEXT(beginproblem());

$showPartialCorrectAnswers = 1;

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
Suppose that
\[ f(x) = $a x \sqrt{$b x^2 + $c}  \]
$BR
$BR
(A) Find all critical values of \(f\). 
If there are no critical values, enter $BBOLD None $EBOLD.  
If there are more than one, enter them separated by commas.
$BR
Critical value(s) = \{ans_rule(12)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (number_list_cmp("None", strings=>['None']) );

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
(B) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is increasing.
$PAR
$PAR
$BBOLD Note: $EBOLD When using interval notation in WeBWorK, you use
$BBOLD I $EBOLD for \(\infty\), $BBOLD -I $EBOLD for \(-\infty\), and
$BBOLD U $EBOLD for the union symbol.  If there are no values that satisfy the
required condition, then enter $BBOLD None $EBOLD.

Increasing:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("(-I,I)", strings=>['None']));

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(C) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is decreasing.
$BR
Decreasing:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("None", strings=>['None']));

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(D) Find the \(x\)-coordinates of all local maxima of \(f\). 
If there are no local maxima, enter $BBOLD None $EBOLD.
If there are more than one, enter them separated by commas.
$PAR
Local maxima at \(x\) = \{ans_rule(10)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (number_list_cmp("None", strings=>['None']) );

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(E) Find the \(x\)-coordinates of all local minima of \(f\). 
If there are no local minima, enter $BBOLD None $EBOLD.
If there are more than one, enter them separated by commas.
$PAR
Local minima at \(x\) = \{ans_rule(10)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (number_list_cmp("None", strings=>['None']) );

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(F) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is concave up.
$BR
Concave up:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("(0,I)", strings=>['None']));

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(G) Use interval notation to indicate where \( f(x) \) is concave down.
$BR
Concave down:
$BR
\{ans_rule(25)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (interval_cmp("(-I,0)", strings=>['None']));

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));
$BR
(H) Find all inflection points of \(f\). 
If there are no inflection points, enter $BBOLD None $EBOLD.
If there are more than one, enter them separated by commas.
$BR
Inflection point(s) at \(x\) = \{ans_rule(12)\}
$PAR
$PAR
EOT

@answers = (number_list_cmp(0, strings=>['None']) );

ANS(@answers );

TEXT(EV2(<<EOT));

(I) Use all of the preceding information to sketch a
graph of \(f\).  When you're finished, enter a $BBOLD 1 $EBOLD in the box
below.
$BR
$BR
Graph Complete: \{ans_rule(12)\}
$PAR
$PAR

EOT

@answers = (num_cmp(1) );

ANS(@answers );

ENDDOCUMENT();        # This should be the last executable line in the problem.
